# CHAPTER 3: DESIGN AND IMPLEMENTATION

## PART A: SYSTEM DESIGN

### 3.1 System Architecture

StudyVault follows a layered web application architecture with four primary layers.

**1. Client Layer**
The user interacts with the system through a standard web browser (Chrome, Firefox, Edge). All three roles — Student, Faculty, and Admin — access role-specific pages rendered by Jinja2 templates. JavaScript handles client-side interactivity such as AJAX requests for note approval actions and AI tool invocations.

**2. Application Layer**
The core of the system is a FastAPI application served by a Uvicorn ASGI server. The application is divided into modular routers: [auth.py](file:///C:/Users/Lenovo/studyvault/app/routes/auth.py) handles registration, login, logout, and role selection; [student.py](file:///C:/Users/Lenovo/studyvault/app/routes/student.py) manages the dashboard, upload, browse, favorites, AI tools, messaging, and forum; [faculty.py](file:///C:/Users/Lenovo/studyvault/app/routes/faculty.py) handles approvals, preview, announcements, and messaging; [admin.py](file:///C:/Users/Lenovo/studyvault/create_admin.py) controls user management, note moderation, reports, and settings; [reports.py](file:///C:/Users/Lenovo/studyvault/app/routes/reports.py) handles content reporting by users. A custom [NotificationMiddleware](file:///C:/Users/Lenovo/studyvault/app/main.py#37-71) intercepts every request to fetch unread notification counts and populates the session context before the view renders, so the notification bell is always accurate.

**3. AI Layer**
The Groq API using the `llama-3.1-8b-instant` model provides two types of intelligence. Safety Analysis runs at upload time and returns a structured JSON report scoring content on six categories: plagiarism, academic misconduct, copyright violation, spam, inappropriate content, and malicious content. Study Tools provide summarisation, flashcard generation, Q&A, and study guide generation for students on-demand. Text extraction is handled before passing content to the AI using PyPDF2 for PDFs, pytesseract for images, and python-docx or python-pptx for office documents.

**4. Data Layer**
MongoDB stores all application data in the `studyvault` database via PyMongo. Uploaded files are stored in the local `uploads/` directory and served via a static file mount at `/uploads`.

