# CHAPTER 4: TESTING

## 4.1 Testing Approach

Testing was performed manually in three phases. First, individual routes and functions were tested independently using direct browser access and Postman for POST endpoints. Second, each feature was tested end-to-end through the browser interface with all three user roles. Third, input forms were tested with missing, invalid, and boundary-case values. Error responses and edge cases were validated by checking browser output, server console logs, and MongoDB collection states.

## 4.2 Types of Testing Performed

- **Functional Testing:** Each feature was verified to function as specified — upload, approve, reject, download, message, notify.
- **Validation Testing:** Form inputs were tested for required field enforcement, type mismatches, and out-of-range values.
- **Security Testing:** Role cross-login, unauthorized route access, and timing attack resistance were tested.
- **Module Testing:** Each router module (auth, student, faculty, admin, reports) was tested in isolation with specific inputs and expected outputs.
- **Boundary Testing:** File type enforcement with allowed and disallowed extensions; empty file submissions; very large inputs to AI text processing.

